04950nam a22007095i 9780814724958DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814724958  a(DE-B1597)548458  a(OCoLC)870951047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD8039.M62bU6132 2016 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a331.762233509748090342231 aArnold, Andrew B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFueling the Gilded Age :bRailroads, Miners, and Disorder in Pennsylvania Coal Country /cAndrew B. Arnold. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture, Labor, History ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAbout Lewis Hine’s Photographs -- tIntroduction: Railroads, Miners, and Disorder in 1 the Gilded Age, 1870–1900 -- tPart I. Hubris -- t1. Cultural: Coal Mining and Community, 1872 -- t2. Formal: The Right to Strike, 1875 -- t3. Secret: Regional Leadership Networks, 1875–1882 -- tPart II. Humility -- t4. Compromise: The Great Upheaval in Coal, 1886 -- tPart III. Stalemate -- t5. Origins: New Organizational Forms, 1886–1890 -- t6. Association: Organization and Industry, 1890–1894 -- t7. National Scale: A Living Wage for Capital and for Labor, 1895–1902 -- tConclusion: Failures of Order in the Gilded Age -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf the railroads won the Gilded Age, the coal industry lost it. Railroads epitomized modern management, high technology, and vast economies of scale. By comparison, the coal industry was embarrassingly primitive. Miners and operators dug coal, bought it, and sold it in 1900 in the same ways that they had for generations. In the popular imagination, coal miners epitomized anti-modern forces as the so-called “Molly Maguire” terrorists. Yet the sleekly modern railroads were utterly dependent upon the disorderly coal industry. Railroad managers demanded that coal operators and miners accept the purely subordinate role implied by their status. They refused. Fueling the Gilded Age shows how disorder in the coal industry disrupted the strategic plans of the railroads. It does so by expertly intertwining the history of two industries-railroads and coal mining-that historians have generally examined from separate vantage points. It shows the surprising connections between railroad management and miner organizing; railroad freight rate structure and coal mine operations; railroad strategy and strictly local legal precedents. It combines social, economic, and institutional approaches to explain the Gilded Age from the perspective of the relative losers of history rather than the winners. It beckons readers to examine the still-unresolved nature of America’s national conundrum: how to reconcile the competing demands of national corporations, local businesses, and employees.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCoal minerszPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCoal mines and miningzPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCoal mining - Pennsylvania - History - 19th century. 0aLabor movementzPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLabor unionszPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aRailroadszPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107289960 cprintz978081476498540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814724958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814724958/original  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2